1
00:00:00,720 --> 00:00:04,320
Today, I'm chatting with Terence 
Tao, who needs no introduction. 

2
00:00:04,320 --> 00:00:10,400
Terence, I want to begin by having you retell 
the story of how Kepler discovered the laws of  

3
00:00:10,400 --> 00:00:15,280
planetary motion because I think this will be a 
great jumping off point to talk about AI for math. 

4
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:17,840
I've always had an amateur interest in astronomy. 

5
00:00:18,480 --> 00:00:22,800
I've loved stories of how the early astronomers 
worked out the nature of the universe. 

6
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:30,080
Kepler was building on the work of Copernicus, who 
was himself building on the work of Aristarchus. 

7
00:00:31,040 --> 00:00:36,160
Copernicus very famously proposed the 
heliocentric model, that instead of the  

8
00:00:36,160 --> 00:00:40,800
planets and the Sun going around the Earth, the 
Sun was at the center of the solar system and the  

9
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:45,120
other planets were going around the Sun.
Copernicus proposed that the orbits of  

10
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:50,240
the planets were perfect circles.
His theory fit the observations  

11
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:55,360
that the Greeks, the Arabs, and the 
Indians had worked out over centuries. 

12
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:04,160
Kepler learned about these theories in his 
studies, and he made this observation that the  

13
00:01:04,160 --> 00:01:09,840
ratios of the size of the orbits that Copernicus 
predicted seemed to have some geometric meaning. 

14
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:19,520
He started proposing that if you take the orbit 
of the Earth and you enclose it in a cube,  

15
00:01:20,400 --> 00:01:25,440
the outer sphere that encloses the cube almost 
perfectly matched the orbit of Mars, and so forth. 

16
00:01:26,320 --> 00:01:30,640
There were six planets known at the time and five 
gaps between them, and there were five perfect  

17
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:35,760
Platonic solids: the cube, the tetrahedron, 
icosahedron, octahedron, and dodecahedron. 

18
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:38,880
So he had this theory, which he 
thought was absolutely beautiful,  

19
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:44,960
that you could inscribe these Platonic 
solids between the spheres of the planets. 

20
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:50,320
It seemed to fit, and it seemed to him that 
God's design of the planets was matching this  

21
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:56,880
mathematical perfection of the Platonic solids.
He needed data to confirm this theory. 

22
00:01:56,880 --> 00:02:02,160
At the time, there was only one really 
high-quality dataset in existence. 

23
00:02:02,160 --> 00:02:08,160
Tycho Brahe, this very wealthy, 
eccentric Danish astronomer,  

24
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:12,560
had managed to convince the Danish government 
to fund this extremely expensive observatory. 

25
00:02:12,560 --> 00:02:18,240
In fact, it was an entire island where he had 
taken decades of observations of all the planets,  

26
00:02:18,240 --> 00:02:23,600
like Mars and Jupiter, at least every night for 
which the weather was clear, with the naked eye. 

27
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:28,560
He was the last of the naked-eye astronomers.
He had all this data which Kepler  

28
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:32,240
could use to confirm his theory.
Kepler started working with Tycho,  

29
00:02:32,240 --> 00:02:37,280
but Tycho was very jealous of the data.
He only gave him little bits of it at a time. 

30
00:02:38,960 --> 00:02:43,600
Kepler eventually just stole the data.
He copied it and had to have a fight with  

31
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:48,640
Brahe's descendants.
He did get the data,  

32
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:53,040
and then he worked out, to his disappointment, 
that his beautiful theory didn't quite work. 

33
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:57,840
The data was off from his Platonic 
solid theory by 10% or something. 

34
00:02:57,840 --> 00:03:02,800
He tried all kinds of fudges, moving the 
circles around, and it didn't quite work. 

35
00:03:02,800 --> 00:03:08,320
But he worked on this problem for years and years, 
and eventually, he figured out how to use the data  

36
00:03:08,320 --> 00:03:15,840
to work out the actual orbits of the planets.
That was an incredibly clever,  

37
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:20,640
genius amount of data analysis.
And then he worked out that the  

38
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:24,800
orbits were actually ellipses, not 
circles, which was shocking for him. 

39
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:30,560
So he worked out the two laws of planetary 
motion: the ellipses, and also that equal  

40
00:03:30,560 --> 00:03:37,040
areas sweep out equal times.
Then ten years later, after  

41
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:42,320
collecting a lot of data—the furthest planets 
like Saturn and Jupiter were the hardest for  

42
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:50,800
him to work out—he finally worked out this 
third law, that the time it takes for a  

43
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:55,680
planet to complete its orbit was proportional 
to some power of the distance to the Sun. 

44
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:58,160
These are the three famous 
Kepler's laws of motion. 

45
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:04,080
He had no explanation for them.
It was all driven by experiment,  

46
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:09,520
and it took Newton a century later to give a 
theory that explained all three laws at once. 

47
00:04:09,520 --> 00:04:16,400
The take I want to try on you is that 
Kepler was a high-temperature LLM. 

48
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:22,800
Newton comes up with this explanation of why 
the three laws of planetary motion must be true. 

49
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:26,400
Of course, the way that Kepler discovers 
the laws of planetary motion, or figures  

50
00:04:26,400 --> 00:04:29,760
out the relative orbits of the different 
planets, is as you say a work of genius. 

51
00:04:29,760 --> 00:04:33,680
But through his career, he's 
just trying random relationships. 

52
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:38,000
In fact, in the book in which he writes 
down the third law of planetary motion,  

53
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:44,080
it's an aside on The Harmonics of the World, 
which is just a book about how all these different  

54
00:04:44,080 --> 00:04:46,720
planets have these different harmonies.
And the reason there's so much famine  

55
00:04:46,720 --> 00:04:50,320
and misery on Earth is because the Earth 
is mi-fa-mi, that's the note of Earth. 

56
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:54,240
It's all this random astrology, but 
in there is the cube-square law,  

57
00:04:54,240 --> 00:05:00,240
which tells you what relationship the period 
has to a planet's distance from the Sun. 

58
00:05:00,800 --> 00:05:08,880
As you were detailing, if you add that to 
Newton's F=ma and the equation for centripetal  

59
00:05:08,880 --> 00:05:12,880
acceleration, you get the inverse-square law.
And so Newton works that out. 

60
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:18,880
But the reason I think this is an interesting 
story is that I feel LLMs can do the kind of  

61
00:05:18,880 --> 00:05:22,480
thing of trying random relationships for 
twenty years, some of which make no sense,  

62
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:27,600
as long as there's a verifiable data bank like 
Brahe's dataset. "Ok, I'm going to try out random  

63
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:32,800
things about musical notes, Platonic objects, 
or different geometries, I have this bias that  

64
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:36,960
there's some important thing about the geometry 
of these orbits." Then one thing works. As long  

65
00:05:36,960 --> 00:05:44,240
as you can verify it, these empirical regularities 
can then drive actual deep scientific progress. 

66
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:48,080
Traditionally, when we talk about the 
history of science, idea generation has  

67
00:05:48,080 --> 00:05:53,520
always been the prestige part of science.
A scientific problem comes with many steps. 

68
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:57,680
You have to identify a problem, and then you have 
to identify a good, fruitful problem to work on. 

69
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:03,120
Then you need to collect data, 
figure out a strategy to analyze  

70
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:07,280
the data, and make a hypothesis.
At this point, you need to propose a  

71
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:11,360
good hypothesis, and then you need to validate.
Then you need to write things up and explain. 

72
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:17,760
There are a dozen different components.
The ones we celebrate are these eureka  

73
00:06:17,760 --> 00:06:26,800
genius moments of idea generation.
Kepler certainly had to cycle through  

74
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:32,080
many ideas, several of which didn't work.
I bet there were many that he didn't even  

75
00:06:32,080 --> 00:06:37,760
publish at all because they just didn't fit.
That's an important part of the process,  

76
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:40,720
