00:17:33,840 --> 00:17:39,840
Often in the history of science when a new theory 
comes up that in retrospect we realize is correct,  

192
00:17:39,840 --> 00:17:45,920
it seems to make implications that either 
make no sense because they're wrong, and we  

193
00:17:45,920 --> 00:17:49,760
realize later on why they're wrong, or they're 
correct but seem wildly implausible at the time. 

194
00:17:50,560 --> 00:17:56,080
As you talked about, Aristarchus had 
heliocentrism in the third century BC. 

195
00:17:58,480 --> 00:18:03,520
The ancient Athenians were like, "This can't be 
because if the earth is going around the sun,  

196
00:18:03,520 --> 00:18:08,000
we should see the relative position of the stars 
change as we're going around the sun, and the only  

197
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:13,440
way that wouldn't be the case is if they're so 
far away that you don't notice any parallax,"  

198
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:16,320
which is actually the correct implication.
But there's times when the implication is  

199
00:18:16,320 --> 00:18:19,360
incorrect and we just need to graduate 
to a better level of understanding. 

200
00:18:19,360 --> 00:18:25,360
Leibniz would chide Newton and disagree with 
Newton's theory of gravity on the basis that  

201
00:18:25,360 --> 00:18:31,680
it implied action at a distance, and they 
didn't know the mechanism, and Newton himself  

202
00:18:31,680 --> 00:18:34,880
was sort of stunned that inertial mass and 
gravitational mass were the same quantity. 

203
00:18:34,880 --> 00:18:39,360
All these things later were resolved by 
Einstein. But it was still progress. So  

204
00:18:39,360 --> 00:18:45,520
the question for a system of peer review for 
AI would be: even if you can falsify a theory,  

205
00:18:45,520 --> 00:18:49,040
how would you notice that it still constitutes 
progress relative to the thing before? 

206
00:18:49,920 --> 00:18:54,320
Often, the ultimately correct theory 
initially is worse in many ways. 

207
00:18:54,960 --> 00:19:00,000
Copernicus's theory of the planets was 
less accurate than Ptolemy's theory. 

208
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:06,800
Geocentrism had been developed for a 
millennium by that point, and they had  

209
00:19:06,800 --> 00:19:12,960
made many tweaks and increasingly complicated 
ad hoc fixes to make it more and more accurate. 

210
00:19:13,920 --> 00:19:16,880
Copernicus's theory was a lot 
simpler but much less accurate. 

211
00:19:16,880 --> 00:19:20,640
It was only Kepler that made it 
more accurate than Ptolemy's theory. 

212
00:19:21,200 --> 00:19:26,480
Science is always a work in progress.
When you only get part of the solution,  

213
00:19:27,040 --> 00:19:34,000
it looks worse than a theory which is incorrect 
but somehow has been completed to the point  

214
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:42,720
where it kind of answers all the questions.
As you say, Newton's theory had big mysteries. 

215
00:19:42,720 --> 00:19:45,760
They had the equivalence of mass 
and action at a distance, which  

216
00:19:45,760 --> 00:19:53,120
were only resolved with a very conceptually 
different approach centuries afterwards. 

217
00:19:54,880 --> 00:19:59,040
Often progress has to be made not by 
adding more theories, but by deleting  

218
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:06,080
some assumptions that you have in your mind.
One reason why geocentrism held on for so long  

219
00:20:06,080 --> 00:20:10,720
is we had this idea that objects 
naturally want to stay at rest. 

220
00:20:10,720 --> 00:20:14,240
This is the Aristotelian notion of physics, 
and so the idea that the Earth was moving…  

221
00:20:14,240 --> 00:20:19,200
How come we weren't all falling over?
Once you have Newton's laws of motion—an  

222
00:20:19,200 --> 00:20:23,520
object in motion remains in motion 
and so forth—then it makes sense. 

223
00:20:25,280 --> 00:20:30,480
Conceptually, it's a very big leap to 
realize that the Earth is in motion. 

224
00:20:30,480 --> 00:20:37,040
It doesn't feel like it's in motion.
The biggest advances, like Darwin's  

225
00:20:37,040 --> 00:20:41,840
theory of evolution, is the idea 
that species are not static. 

226
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:47,840
This is not obvious because you 
don't see evolution in your lifetime. 

227
00:20:47,840 --> 00:20:55,360
Well, now we actually can, but 
it seems permanent and static. 

228
00:20:57,680 --> 00:21:03,440
Right now we're going through a cognitive version 
of the Copernican revolution, where we used to  

229
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:07,040
think that human intelligence is the center of 
the universe, and now we're seeing that there are  

230
00:21:07,040 --> 00:21:12,560
very different types of intelligence out there 
with very different strengths and weaknesses. 

231
00:21:14,640 --> 00:21:18,240
Our assessment of which tasks require 
intelligence, which ones don't,  

232
00:21:18,960 --> 00:21:25,280
has to be reordered quite a bit.
Trying to fit AI into our theories  

233
00:21:25,280 --> 00:21:30,160
of scientific progress and what is hard and 
what is easy, we're struggling quite a lot. 

234
00:21:30,160 --> 00:21:32,880
We have to ask questions that we've 
never really had to ask before. 

235
00:21:32,880 --> 00:21:35,920
Or maybe the philosophers had, but 
now we all have to deal with it. 

236
00:21:35,920 --> 00:21:39,600
This brings up a topic I've 
been very curious about. 

237
00:21:39,600 --> 00:21:43,600
You mentioned Darwin's theory of evolution.
There's this book, The Clockwork Universe  

238
00:21:43,600 --> 00:21:47,360
by Edward Dolnick, which covers a lot of 
this era of history we're talking about. 

239
00:21:47,360 --> 00:21:52,320
He has this interesting observation in there.
The Origin of Species was published in 1859. 

240
00:21:52,320 --> 00:21:57,680
Principia Mathematica was published in 1687.
So The Origin of Species comes out two centuries  

241
00:21:57,680 --> 00:21:59,840
after Principia.
Conceptually,  

242
00:21:59,840 --> 00:22:04,945
it seems like Darwin's theory is simpler.
There's a contemporaneous biologist to Darwin,  

243
00:22:04,945 --> 00:22:09,440
Thomas Huxley, who reads The Origin of Species and 
he says, "How stupid not to have thought of that." 

244
00:22:09,440 --> 00:22:12,080
Nobody ever says that about 
Principia, chiding themselves  

245
00:22:12,080 --> 00:22:17,920
for not having beaten Newton to gravity.
So there's a question of why did it take longer? 

246
00:22:17,920 --> 00:22:20,400
It seems like a big part of the 
reason is what you were saying. 

247
00:22:20,400 --> 00:22:23,600
The evidence for natural selection is overwhelming 
in a certain sense, but it's cumulative and  

248
00:22:23,600 --> 00:22:27,520
retrospective, whereas Newton can 
just say, "Here are my equations. 

249
00:22:27,520 --> 00:22:31,440
Let me see the moon's orbital 
period and its distance,  

250
00:22:31,440 --> 00:22:37,040
and if it lines up, then we've made progress."
Lucretius actually had this idea that species  

251
00:22:37,040 --> 00:22:42,880
adapted to their environment in the first 
century BC but nobody really talks about it  

252
00:22:42,880 --> 00:22:48,320
until Darwin because Lucretius couldn't run some 
experiment and force people to pay attention. 

253
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:54,560
I wonder if we'll in retrospect end up seeing 
much more progress in domains which have this  

254
00:22:54,560 --> 00:23:00,000
kind of tight data loop where you can 
verify them quite easily, even though  

255
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,400
they're conceptually much more difficult.
I think one aspect of science is that it's not  

256
00:23:04,400 --> 00:23:08,720
just creating a new theory and validating 
it, but communicating it to others. 

257
00:23:09,360 --> 00:23:15,840
Darwin was an amazing science communicator.
He wrote in English, in natural language. I'm  

258
00:23:15,840 --> 00:23:20,240
speaking like a—
No Lean. 

259
00:23:22,560 --> 00:23:30,000
I have to get out of my technical mindset.
He spoke in plain English, didn't use equations,  

260
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:36,960
and he synthesized a lot of disparate facts.
Little pieces of evolution had been worked out in  

261
00:23:36,960 --> 00:23:42,960
the past, but he had this very compelling vision.
Again, he was still missing things. 

262
00:23:42,960 --> 00:23:47,920
He didn't know the mechanism for 
heredity, he didn't have DNA. 

263
00:23:49,920 --> 00:23:55,920
But his writing style was persuasive, and 
that helped a lot. Newton wrote in Latin.  

264
00:23:57,600 --> 00:24:02,720
He had invented entire new areas of 
mathematics just to explain what he was doing. 

265
00:24:02,720 --> 00:24:06,960
He was also from an era where scientists 
were much more secretive and competitive. 

266
00:24:07,600 --> 00:24:10,880
Academia is still competitive, but it 
was even worse back in Newton's day. 

267
00:24:11,920 --> 00:24:16,560
He held back some of his best insights because 
he didn't want his rivals to get any advantage. 

268
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:20,800
He was also a somewhat unpleasant 
person from what I gather. 

269
00:24:23,040 --> 00:24:28,480
It was only a couple of decades after Newton 
when other scientists explained his work in  

270
00:24:28,480 --> 00:24:39,120
much simpler terms that they became widespread.
The art of exposition and making a case and  

271
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:43,440
creating a narrative is also a 
very important part of science. 

272
00:24:45,280 --> 00:24:50,320
If you have the data, it helps, but people need 
to be convinced, otherwise they will not push  

273
00:24:50,320 --> 00:24:56,560
it further or take the initial investment 
to learn your theory and really explore it. 

274
00:24:58,000 --> 00:25:00,640
That's another thing which is really 
hard to reinforcement learn on. 

275
00:25:01,440 --> 00:25:05,600
How can you score how persuasive you are?
Well, there are entire marketing  

276
00:25:05,600 --> 00:25:08,720
departments trying to do this.
Maybe it's good that AI is not  

277
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:16,080
yet optimized to be persuasive.
There's a social aspect to science. 

278
00:25:19,120 --> 00:25:23,520
Even though we pride ourselves on having an 
objective side to it, where there's data and  

279
00:25:23,520 --> 00:25:28,480
experiment and validation, we still have 
to tell stories and convince our fellow  

280
00:25:28,480 --> 00:25:41,520
scientists. That's a soft, squishy thing. It's 
a combination of data and painting a narrative,  

281
00:25:41,520 --> 00:25:46,560
and it's a narrative of gaps.
Even with Darwin, as I said, there  

282
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:51,200
were pieces of his theory he could not explain.
But he could still make a case that in the future,  

283
00:25:51,200 --> 00:25:54,960
people would find transitional 
forms, that they would find the  

284
00:25:54,960 --> 00:26:01,280
mechanism of inheritance, and they did.
I don't know how you can quantify that  

285
00:26:01,280 --> 00:26:04,640
in such a precise way that you can 
start doing reinforcement learning. 

286
00:26:06,320 --> 00:26:10,880
Maybe that will be forever 
the human side of science. 

287
00:26:10,880 --> 00:26:16,880
One takeaway I had from reading and watching your 
