of the information they had because data was  

297
00:27:04,400 --> 00:27:10,160
the bottleneck. It still is the bottleneck. 
It's really hard to collect astronomical data. 

298
00:27:10,160 --> 00:27:20,160
Astronomers are world-class in 
extracting all kinds of conclusions  

299
00:27:20,160 --> 00:27:26,400
from little traces of data, almost like Sherlock.
I hear that for a lot of quant hedge funds, their  

300
00:27:26,400 --> 00:27:31,280
preferred hire is an astronomy PhD, actually.
They are also very interested for other reasons  

301
00:27:31,280 --> 00:27:35,120
in extracting signals from 
various random bits of data. 

302
00:27:35,120 --> 00:27:39,040
Okay, speaking of clever ideas, 
one of my listeners, Shawn,  

303
00:27:39,040 --> 00:27:44,160
solved the puzzle that Jane Street made for my 
audience and posted a great walkthrough on X. 

304
00:27:44,160 --> 00:27:50,000
For context, Jane Street trained a ResNet, 
shuffled all 96 layers, and then challenged  

305
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:54,640
people to put them back in the right order using 
only the model's outputs and training data. 

306
00:27:54,640 --> 00:27:58,880
You can't brute force this – there's more 
possible orderings than atoms in the universe. 

307
00:27:58,880 --> 00:28:01,440
So Shawn broke the problem 
into two different parts. 

308
00:28:01,440 --> 00:28:06,880
First, pair the layers into 48 different blocks.
And second, put those blocks in the right order. 

309
00:28:06,880 --> 00:28:11,360
For pairing, Shawn realized that in 
a well-trained ResNet, the product of  

310
00:28:11,360 --> 00:28:16,640
two weight matrices in a residual block should 
have a distinctive negative diagonal pattern. 

311
00:28:16,640 --> 00:28:20,400
This arises as a way for the model to keep the 
residual stream from growing out of control. 

312
00:28:20,400 --> 00:28:23,440
From this insight, he was able 
to recover the right pairings. 

313
00:28:23,440 --> 00:28:28,080
For ordering, Shawn noticed that the model 
seemed to improve if he sorted the blocks by  

314
00:28:28,080 --> 00:28:31,680
the size of their residual contributions.
Starting with that rough approximation,  

315
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:36,640
he combined a clever ranking heuristic with 
local swaps to recover the exact right order. 

316
00:28:36,640 --> 00:28:39,120
His full walkthrough is linked in the description. 

317
00:28:39,120 --> 00:28:40,960
Don't worry if you didn't get 
to this puzzle in time, though. 

318
00:28:40,960 --> 00:28:44,960
