382
00:34:57,280 --> 00:35:00,640
different problems at the same time.
But once AIs reach Terence Tao-level,  

383
00:35:00,640 --> 00:35:03,920
they could do that.
Once they reach intermediate levels,  

384
00:35:03,920 --> 00:35:09,520
they could do the intermediate version of that.
The same reason that we should be bearish now is  

385
00:35:09,520 --> 00:35:12,880
the reason we should be especially bullish.
Not even when they achieve superhuman  

386
00:35:12,880 --> 00:35:15,040
intelligence, but just when they 
achieve human-level intelligence,  

387
00:35:15,040 --> 00:35:19,680
because their human-level intelligence 
is qualitatively wider and more powerful  

388
00:35:19,680 --> 00:35:24,320
than our human-level intelligence.
I agree. They excel at breadth,  

389
00:35:24,320 --> 00:35:29,920
and humans excel at depth, human experts at 
least. I think they're very complementary.  

390
00:35:30,880 --> 00:35:37,520
But our current way of doing math and science 
is focused on depth because that's where human  

391
00:35:37,520 --> 00:35:45,600
expertise is, because humans can't do breadth.
We have to redesign the way we do science to take  

392
00:35:45,600 --> 00:35:49,360
full advantage of this breadth 
capability that we now have. 

393
00:35:51,120 --> 00:35:55,280
We should have a lot more effort in creating 
very broad classes of problems to work on rather  

394
00:35:55,280 --> 00:36:01,440
than one or two really deep, important problems.
We should still have the deep, important problems,  

395
00:36:01,440 --> 00:36:08,960
and humans should still be working on them.
But now we have this other way of doing science. 

396
00:36:10,160 --> 00:36:15,360
We can explore entirely new fields of 
science by first getting these broad,  

397
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:21,520
moderately competent AIs to map it out 
and make all the easy observations. 

398
00:36:21,520 --> 00:36:28,560
And then identify certain islands of difficulty, 
which human experts can then come and work on. 

399
00:36:29,120 --> 00:36:34,720
I see very much a future of 
very complementary science. 

400
00:36:34,720 --> 00:36:41,920
Eventually, you would hope to get both breadth 
and depth and somehow get the best of both worlds. 

401
00:36:41,920 --> 00:36:48,880
But we need practice with the breadth side. 
It's too new. We don't even have the paradigms  

402
00:36:48,880 --> 00:36:54,000
to really take full advantage of it.
But we will, and then science will be  

403
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:59,600
unrecognizable after that, I think.
To this point about complementarity,  

404
00:37:00,560 --> 00:37:04,800
programmers have noticed that they're way 
more productive as a result of these AI tools. 

405
00:37:05,680 --> 00:37:09,520
I don't know if you as a mathematician 
feel the same way, but it does seem  

406
00:37:09,520 --> 00:37:16,320
like one big difference between vibe coding 
and vibe researching is that with software,  

407
00:37:16,320 --> 00:37:21,360
the whole point is to have some 
effect on the world through your work. 

408
00:37:21,360 --> 00:37:25,040
If it leads to you better understanding 
a problem or coming up with some clean  

409
00:37:25,040 --> 00:37:29,120
abstraction to embody in your code, 
that is instrumental to the end goal. 

410
00:37:29,120 --> 00:37:34,560
Whereas with research, the reason we care 
about solving the Millennium Prize Problems  

411
00:37:34,560 --> 00:37:39,600
is that presumably that in the process of 
solving them, we discover new mathematical  

412
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:45,840
objects or new techniques that advance our 
civilization's understanding of mathematics. 

413
00:37:45,840 --> 00:37:50,800
So the proof is instrumental 
to the intermediate work. 

414
00:37:50,800 --> 00:37:57,040
I don't know if you agree with that dichotomy 
or if that in any way will explain the relative  

415
00:37:57,040 --> 00:38:03,200
uplift we'll see in software versus research.
Certainly in math, the process is often more  

416
00:38:03,200 --> 00:38:06,320
important than the problem itself.
The problem is kind of a proxy  

417
00:38:06,320 --> 00:38:09,360
for measuring progress.
I think even in software,  

418
00:38:09,360 --> 00:38:15,120
there are different types of software tasks.
If you just create a webpage that does the same  

419
00:38:15,120 --> 00:38:19,600
thing that a thousand other webpages 
do, there's no skill to be learned. 

420
00:38:19,600 --> 00:38:24,000
Well, there is still some skill maybe that 
the individual programmer could pick up. 

421
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:32,480
But for boilerplate-type code, it's something 
that you should definitely offload to AI. 

422
00:38:35,600 --> 00:38:38,000
Sometimes once you make the code, 
you still have to maintain it. 

423
00:38:39,040 --> 00:38:41,920
There are issues with upgrading it and 
making it compatible with other things. 

424
00:38:44,720 --> 00:38:49,520
I've heard programmers report that even 
if an AI can create the first prototype  

425
00:38:50,800 --> 00:38:55,280
of a tool, making it mesh with everything 
else and making it interact with the real  

426
00:38:55,280 --> 00:39:01,920
world in the way they want is an ongoing process.
If you don't have the skills that you pick up from  

427
00:39:03,520 --> 00:39:09,440
writing the code, that may impact your 
ability to maintain it down the road. 

428
00:39:10,640 --> 00:39:19,440
So yes, certainly mathematicians, we've used 
problems to build intuition and to train people  

429
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:25,040
to have a good idea of what's true, what to 
expect, what is provable, and what is difficult. 

430
00:39:26,480 --> 00:39:30,480
Just getting the answers right away 
may actually inhibit that process. 

431
00:39:35,280 --> 00:39:37,520
I made a distinction between 
theory and experiment before. 

432
00:39:39,360 --> 00:39:42,240
In most sciences, there's an equal 
division between the theoretical side  

433
00:39:42,240 --> 00:39:46,160
and the experimental side.
Math has been unique in  

434
00:39:46,160 --> 00:39:53,280
that it's almost entirely theoretical.
We place a premium on trying to have coherent,  

435
00:39:53,280 --> 00:39:59,120
clean theories of why things are true and false.
We haven't done many experiments as to,  

436
00:39:59,120 --> 00:40:03,520
if we have two different ways to solve 
a problem, which is more effective. 

437
00:40:04,640 --> 00:40:07,920
We have some intuition, but we haven't done 
large-scale studies where we take a thousand  

438
00:40:07,920 --> 00:40:13,120
problems and just test them.
But we can do that now. 

439
00:40:13,120 --> 00:40:19,520
I think AI-type tools will actually 
revolutionize the experimental side of math,  

440
00:40:19,520 --> 00:40:24,880
where you don't care so much about individual 
problems and the process of solving them,  

441
00:40:24,880 --> 00:40:30,000
but you want to gather large-scale data 
about what things work and what things don't. 

442
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:36,240
The same way that if you're a software 
company and you want to roll out a thousand  

443
00:40:36,240 --> 00:40:39,280
pieces of software, you don't really want to 
handcraft each one and learn lessons from each. 

444
00:40:39,280 --> 00:40:42,000
You just want to find what 
workflows let you scale. 

445
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:49,200
The idea of doing mathematics 
at scale is at its infancy. 

446
00:40:49,200 --> 00:40:52,240
But that's where AI is really 
going to revolutionize the subject. 

447
00:40:53,360 --> 00:40:58,880
I feel like a big crux in these conversations 
about how good AI will be for science is,  

448
00:40:58,880 --> 00:41:04,880
I think you said this, that they're using 
existing techniques and modifying them. 

449
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:09,680
It would be interesting to 
understand how much progress one  

450
00:41:09,680 --> 00:41:14,800
can make simply from using existing techniques.
If I looked at the top math journals, how many of  

451
00:41:15,760 --> 00:41:21,200
the papers are coming up with a new technique, 
whatever that means, versus using existing  

452
00:41:21,200 --> 00:41:27,200
techniques on new problems? What is the overhang? 
If you just applied every known technique to every  

453
00:41:27,200 --> 00:41:32,560
open problem, would that constitute a humongous 
uplift in our civilization's knowledge, or would  

454
00:41:32,560 --> 00:41:38,640
that not be that impressive and useful?
This is a great question, and we don't  

455
00:41:38,640 --> 00:41:44,640
have the data to fully answer it yet.
Certainly, a lot of work that human  

456
00:41:44,640 --> 00:41:50,560
mathematicians do… When you take a new problem, 
one of the first things we do is we look at all  

457
00:41:50,560 --> 00:41:53,920
the standard things that have worked on similar 
problems in the past, and we try them one by one. 

458
00:41:54,640 --> 00:41:59,920
Sometimes that works, and that's still worth 
publishing because the question was important. 

459
00:41:59,920 --> 00:42:01,920
Sometimes they almost work, 
and you have to add one more  

460
00:42:01,920 --> 00:42:08,880
wrinkle to it, and that's also interesting.
But the papers that go into the top journals  

461
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:14,560
are usually ones where the existing methods 
can kind of solve 80% of the problem, but then  

462
00:42:14,560 --> 00:42:20,640
there is this 20% which is resistant and a new 
technique has to be invented to fill in the gaps. 

463
00:42:21,760 --> 00:42:26,960
It's very rare now that a problem gets 
solved with no reliance on past literature,  

464
00:42:26,960 --> 00:42:32,880
where all the ideas come out of nowhere.
That was more common in the past,  

465
00:42:32,880 --> 00:42:42,160
but math is so mature now that it's just so much 
of a handicap to not use the literature first. 

466
00:42:44,800 --> 00:42:49,360
AI tools are getting really good at the 
first part of that, just trying all the  

467
00:42:49,360 --> 00:42:55,760
standard techniques on a problem, often making 
fewer mistakes in applying them than humans. 

468
00:42:55,760 --> 00:43:04,720
They still make mistakes, but I've tested 
these tools on little tasks that I can do,  

469
00:43:04,720 --> 00:43:07,920
and sometimes they pick up errors that I make.
Sometimes I pick up errors that they make. 

470
00:43:07,920 --> 00:43:16,560
It's about a tie right now.
But I haven't yet seen them take the next step. 

471
00:43:17,280 --> 00:43:24,240
When there are holes in the argument where none 
of the things are working, then what do you do? 

472
00:43:25,360 --> 00:43:31,200
They can suggest random things, but often 
I find that trying to chase them down to  

473
00:43:31,200 --> 00:43:34,800
make them work, and finding they don't 
work, wastes more time than it saves. 

474
00:43:38,560 --> 00:43:42,720
I think some fraction of problems that 
we currently think are hard will fall  

475
00:43:42,720 --> 00:43:46,640
from this method, especially the ones 
that haven't received enough attention. 

476
00:43:48,160 --> 00:43:53,600
With the Erdős problems, almost all of the 50 
problems that were solved by AIs were ones for  

477
00:43:53,600 --> 00:43:57,520
which there was basically no literature.
Erdős posed the problem once or twice. 

478
00:43:59,200 --> 00:44:02,720
Maybe some people tried it casually and couldn't 
do it, but they never wrote up anything. 

479
00:44:03,920 --> 00:44:08,640
But it turned out that there was a solution, 
and it was just combining this one obscure  

480
00:44:08,640 --> 00:44:12,720
technique that not many people know about 
with some other result in the literature. 

481
00:44:12,720 --> 00:44:17,440
That's the median level of what AI can 
accomplish, and that's really great. 

482
00:44:17,440 --> 00:44:22,880
It clears out 50 of these problems.
So I think you will see some isolated successes. 

483
00:44:24,320 --> 00:44:28,080
But what we found… Some people have done 
large-scale sweeps of these Erdős problems. 

484
00:44:29,360 --> 00:44:32,320
If you only focus on the success 
stories, the ones that get broadcast  

485
00:44:32,320 --> 00:44:35,840
on social media, it looks amazing.
All these problems that haven't been  

486
00:44:35,840 --> 00:44:40,720
solved for decades, now they're falling.
But whenever we do a systematic study,  

487
00:44:40,720 --> 00:44:44,800
on any given problem an AI tool has 
a success rate of maybe 1% or 2%. 

488
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:50,800
It's just that they can buy scale, and you 
just pick the winners. It looks great. I  

489
00:44:50,800 --> 00:44:57,120
think there'll be a similar thing happening 
with the hundreds of really prestigious,  

490
00:44:57,120 --> 00:45:03,760
difficult math problems out there.
Some AI may get lucky and actually solve them,  

491
00:45:03,760 --> 00:45:07,840
and there will be some backdoor to solve 
the problem that everyone else missed. 

492
00:45:08,400 --> 00:45:12,880
That will get a lot of publicity.
But then people will try these fancy  

493
00:45:12,880 --> 00:45:16,560
tools on their own favorite problem, and they 
will again experience the 1% to 2% success rate. 

494
00:45:18,480 --> 00:45:24,560
There'll be a lot of noise amongst the signal 
of when they're working and when they're not. 

495
00:45:28,720 --> 00:45:32,640
It will be increasingly important to 
collect these really standardized datasets. 

496
00:45:32,640 --> 00:45:38,160
There are efforts now to create a standard set of 
challenge problems for AIs to solve, and not just  

497
00:45:38,160 --> 00:45:43,920
rely on the AI companies to only publish their 
wins and not disclose their negative results. 

498
00:45:44,560 --> 00:45:48,480
That will maybe give more clarity 
as to where we're actually at. 

499
00:45:48,480 --> 00:45:52,080
Although I think it's worth emphasizing how 
much progress in AI it constitutes already,  

500
00:45:52,080 --> 00:45:58,080
to have models that are capable of applying 
some technique that nobody had written down  

501
00:45:58,080 --> 00:46:02,000
as applicable to this particular problem.
The progress is simultaneously amazing  

502
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:05,280
and disappointing.
It is a very strange  

503
00:46:05,280 --> 00:46:11,920
feeling to see these tools in action.
But people also acclimatize really quickly. 

504
00:46:12,800 --> 00:46:16,000
I remember when Google's web 
search came out 20 years ago. 

505
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:18,160
It just blew all the other 
searches out of the water. 

506
00:46:18,160 --> 00:46:23,760
You're getting relevant hits on the 
front page, exactly what you wanted. 

507
00:46:23,760 --> 00:46:26,240
It was amazing, and then after 
a few years, you just took for  

508
00:46:26,240 --> 00:46:35,360
granted that you could Google anything.
2026-level AI would be stunning in 2021. 

509
00:46:35,360 --> 00:46:42,160
A lot of it—face recognition, natural speech, 
doing college-level math problems—we just  

510
00:46:42,160 --> 00:46:45,520
take for granted now.
Speaking of 2026 AI,  

511
00:46:45,520 --> 00:46:52,640
you made a prediction in 2023 that by 2026 
it would be like a colleague in mathematics? 

512
00:46:53,280 --> 00:46:57,280
A trustworthy co-author if used correctly.
Which is looking pretty good in retrospect. 

513
00:46:57,280 --> 00:47:03,440
Yeah, I'm pretty pleased.
So let's see if you can continue this streak. 

514
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:08,800
You personally are 2x more 
productive as a result of AI. 

515
00:47:08,800 --> 00:47:12,640
What year would you say that?
Productivity, I think,  

516
00:47:12,640 --> 00:47:19,280
is not quite a one-dimensional quantity.
I'm definitely noticing that the style  

517
00:47:19,280 --> 00:47:23,440
in which I do mathematics is changing 
quite a bit, and the type of things I do. 

518
00:47:23,440 --> 00:47:26,400
For example, my papers now have a 
lot more code, a lot more pictures,  

519
00:47:29,040 --> 00:47:33,760
because it's so easy to generate these things now.
Some plot which would have taken me hours to do,  

520
00:47:33,760 --> 00:47:37,120
now I can do in minutes.
But in the past, I just wouldn't have  

521
00:47:37,120 --> 00:47:41,040
put the plot in my paper in the first place.
I would just talk about it in words. 

522
00:47:41,600 --> 00:47:50,640
So it's hard to measure what 2x means.
On the one hand, I think the type of  

523
00:47:50,640 --> 00:47:54,080
papers that I would write today, if I 
had to do them without AI assistance,  

524
00:47:54,080 --> 00:47:58,560
would definitely take five times longer.
But I would not write my papers that way. 

525
00:47:58,560 --> 00:48:05,360
5x?
Yeah, but these are auxiliary tasks. 

526
00:48:06,800 --> 00:48:13,520
Things like doing a much deeper literature 
search or supplying a lot more numerics.  

527
00:48:14,480 --> 00:48:24,640
They enrich the paper. The core of what I do, 
actually solving the most difficult part of a  

528
00:48:24,640 --> 00:48:28,080
math problem, hasn't changed too much.
I still use pen and paper for that. 

529
00:48:28,080 --> 00:48:35,760
But there's lots of silly things.
I use an AI agent now to reformat. 

530
00:48:35,760 --> 00:48:39,680
Sometimes if all my parentheses are not quite 
the right size, I used to manually change them  

531
00:48:39,680 --> 00:48:44,400
by hand, and now I can get an AI agent to 
do all that quite nicely in the background. 

532
00:48:46,800 --> 00:48:53,840
They've really sped up lots of secondary tasks.
They haven't yet sped up the core thing that I do,  

533
00:48:53,840 --> 00:48:57,840
but it's allowed me to add 
more things to my papers. 

534
00:49:00,800 --> 00:49:06,000
By the same token, if I were to write a paper 
I wrote in 2020 again—and not add all these  

535
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:10,640
extra features, but just have something of 
the same level of functionality—it actually  

536
00:49:11,600 --> 00:49:17,360
hasn't saved that much time, to be honest.
It's made the papers richer and broader,  

537
00:49:17,360 --> 00:49:22,160
but not necessarily deeper.
You made this distinction between  

538
00:49:22,160 --> 00:49:29,280
artificial cleverness and artificial intelligence.
I would like to better understand those concepts. 

539
00:49:29,280 --> 00:49:36,080
What is an example of intelligence 
that is not just cleverness? 

540
00:49:40,080 --> 00:49:41,920
Intelligence is famously hard to define. 

541
00:49:41,920 --> 00:49:44,000
It's one of these things that 
you know when you see it. 

542
00:49:45,280 --> 00:49:52,480
But when I talk to someone and we're trying to 
collaboratively solve a math problem together,  

543
00:49:53,440 --> 00:49:58,240
there's this conversation where neither of 
us knows how to solve the problem initially. 

544
00:50:00,080 --> 00:50:05,520
One of us has some idea and it looks promising, 
so then we have some sort of prototype strategy. 

545
00:50:06,400 --> 00:50:10,480
We test it, and it doesn't 
work, but then we modify it. 

546
00:50:10,480 --> 00:50:18,240
There's adaptivity and continual 
improvement of the idea over time. 

547
00:50:18,240 --> 00:50:23,760
Eventually, we've systematically mapped 
out what doesn't work and what does work,  

548
00:50:23,760 --> 00:50:28,960
and we can see a path forward, but 
it's evolving with our discussion. 

549
00:50:30,720 --> 00:50:36,560
This isn't quite what the AIs do.
The AIs can mimic this a little bit. 

550
00:50:37,280 --> 00:50:43,280
To go back to this analogy of these jumping 
robots, they can jump and fail, and jump and fail. 

551
00:50:44,320 --> 00:50:52,720
But what they can't do is jump a little bit, reach 
some handhold, stay there, pull other people up,  

552
00:50:52,720 --> 00:50:58,560
and then try to jump from there.
There isn't this cumulative process  

553
00:50:58,560 --> 00:51:04,640
which is built up interactively.
It seems to be a lot more trial and  

554
00:51:04,640 --> 00:51:12,160
error and just repetition: brute force.
It scales, and it can work amazingly  

555
00:51:12,160 --> 00:51:17,520
well in certain contexts.
But this idea of building  

556
00:51:17,520 --> 00:51:23,280
up cumulatively from partial progress 
is what's still not quite there yet. 

557
00:51:23,280 --> 00:51:28,880
Interesting. You're saying if Gemini 3 or 
Claude 4.5, whatever, solves a problem,  

558
00:51:29,760 --> 00:51:32,520
it is not the case that its own 
understanding of math has progressed. 

559
00:51:32,520 --> 00:51:33,440
No.
Or even if it works  

560
00:51:33,440 --> 00:51:36,880
on a problem without solving it, it's not that 
its own understanding of math has progressed. 

561
00:51:36,880 --> 00:51:40,160
Yeah. You run a new session and 
it's forgotten what it just did. 

562
00:51:40,160 --> 00:51:49,840
It has no new skills to build on related problems.
Maybe what you just did is 0.001% of the  

563
00:51:49,840 --> 00:51:53,360
training data for the next generation.
So maybe eventually some of it gets absorbed. 

564
00:51:54,640 --> 00:51:58,000
So Terence talks about the importance 
of decomposing particularly gnarly  

565
00:51:58,000 --> 00:52:03,360
problems into a series of easier chunks.
Even if this doesn't result in the full solution,  

566
00:52:03,360 --> 00:52:07,840
approaching problems in this way helps you build 
up the intuitions and practice the techniques  

567
00:52:07,840 --> 00:52:11,680
that you'll need to keep making progress.
But models today tend to struggle with these  

568
00:52:11,680 --> 00:52:14,720
kinds of problem-solving techniques.
That's where Labelbox comes in. 

569
00:52:14,720 --> 00:52:19,280
Labelbox helps you train models not just to get 
the right answer, but to think the right way. 

570
00:52:19,280 --> 00:52:24,160
They've operationalized these reasoning behaviors 
into rubrics, giving you the ability to evaluate  

571
00:52:24,160 --> 00:52:28,800
every important dimension of a model's output.
These rubrics go beyond simple correctness. 

572
00:52:28,800 --> 00:52:31,840
Did the model reach for the right tools?
Did it check its own work and  

573
00:52:31,840 --> 00:52:35,520
explore alternative paths?
How clear was its response? 

574
00:52:35,520 --> 00:52:40,560
These skills are useful across domains: 
math, physics, finance, psychology, and more. 

575
00:52:40,560 --> 00:52:44,960
And they're becoming increasingly important 
as models take on harder, open-ended problems,  

576
00:52:44,960 --> 00:52:48,800
some of which have multiple solutions and some 
of which we don't even know the solutions to. 

577
00:52:48,800 --> 00:52:52,320
Labelbox can get you rubrics tailored to 
your domain, helping you systematically  

578
00:52:52,320 --> 00:53:00,640
measure and shape how your models think.
Learn more at labelbox.com/dwarkesh. 

579
00:53:00,640 --> 00:53:06,480
One big question I have is how plausible is it 
that if we just keep training AIs—they get better  

580
00:53:06,480 --> 00:53:12,000
and better at solving problems in Lean—that they 
will continue to solve more and more impressive  

581
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:18,000
problems, and then we will be surprised at how 
little insight we got from some Lean solution  

582
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:22,000
to proving the Riemann hypothesis or something.
Or do you think it is a necessary condition of  

583
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:25,360
solving the Riemann hypothesis, even by 
an AI that is doing it entirely in Lean,  

584
00:53:25,360 --> 00:53:32,880
that the constructions and definitions 
created in the Lean program have to  

585
00:53:32,880 --> 00:53:38,480
advance our understanding of mathematics?
Or could it just be assembly code gobbledygook? 

586
00:53:40,000 --> 00:53:44,320
We don't know. Some problems have been 
basically solved by pure brute force. 

587
00:53:44,320 --> 00:53:49,360
The four color theorem is a famous example.
We have still not found a conceptually elegant  

588
00:53:49,360 --> 00:53:56,400
proof of this theorem, and maybe we never will.
Some problems may only be solvable by splitting  

589
00:53:56,400 --> 00:54:00,560
into an enormous number of 
cases and doing brute force,  

590
00:54:00,560 --> 00:54:08,560
uninsightful computer analysis on each case.
Part of the reason we prize problems like  

591
00:54:08,560 --> 00:54:14,960
the Riemann hypothesis is that we're 
pretty sure a new type of mathematics  

592
00:54:14,960 --> 00:54:18,960
has to be created, or a new connection between 
two previously unconnected areas of mathematics  

593
00:54:18,960 --> 00:54:24,560
has to be discovered to make this work.
We don't even know what the shape of the solution  

594
00:54:24,560 --> 00:54:30,400
is, but it doesn't feel like a problem that will 
be solved just by exhaustively checking cases. 

595
00:54:30,400 --> 00:54:37,280
Or it could be false actually.
Okay, there is an unlikely scenario  

596
00:54:37,280 --> 00:54:42,320
that the hypothesis is false, and you 
can just compute a zero off the line,  

597
00:54:42,320 --> 00:54:51,040
and a massive computer calculation verifies 
it. That would be very disappointing. I do  

598
00:54:51,040 --> 00:54:58,160
feel that fully autonomous, one-shot approaches 
are not the right approach for these problems. 

599
00:54:59,200 --> 00:55:04,720
You'll get a lot more mileage out of the interplay 
of humans collaborating with these tools. 

600
00:55:08,080 --> 00:55:14,560
I can see one of these problems 
being solved by smart humans  

601
00:55:14,560 --> 00:55:20,560
assisted by extremely powerful AI tools.
But the exact dynamic may be very different  

602
00:55:20,560 --> 00:55:24,480
from what we envision right now.
It could be a collaboration of  

603
00:55:24,480 --> 00:55:35,200
a type that just doesn't exist yet.
There may be a way to generate a million variants  

604
00:55:35,200 --> 00:55:41,920
of the Riemann zeta function and do AI-assisted 
data analysis to discover some pattern connecting  

605
00:55:41,920 --> 00:55:46,400
them that we didn't know about before.
This lets you transform the problem  

606
00:55:46,400 --> 00:55:51,200
into a different area of mathematics.
There could be all kinds of scenarios. 

607
00:55:51,200 --> 00:55:59,840
Suppose the AI figures it out, and latent in 
the Lean is some brand-new construction which,  

608
00:55:59,840 --> 00:56:04,720
if we realized its significance, we would be 
able to apply in all these different situations. 

609
00:56:04,720 --> 00:56:11,600
How would we even recognize it?
Again, a very naive question, but if you come  

610
00:56:11,600 --> 00:56:17,040
up with the equivalent of Descartes' idea that 
you can have a coordinate system unifying algebra  

611
00:56:17,040 --> 00:56:20,960
and geometry, in Lean code it would just look 
like R→R, and it wouldn't look that significant. 

612
00:56:22,560 --> 00:56:26,160
I'm sure there are other constructions 
which have this kind of property. 

613
00:56:26,160 --> 00:56:29,520
The beauty of formalizing a proof in 
something like Lean is that you can take  

614
00:56:29,520 --> 00:56:39,040
any piece of it and study it atomically.
When I read a paper which solves some  

615
00:56:39,040 --> 00:56:42,640
difficult problem, there's often a 
big sequence of lemmas and theorems. 

616
00:56:44,880 --> 00:56:48,480
Ideally, the author will talk their way 
through what's important and what's not. 

617
00:56:48,480 --> 00:56:52,880
But sometimes they don't reveal what steps 
were the important ones and which ones  

618
00:56:52,880 --> 00:56:59,360
were just boilerplate, standard steps.
You can study each lemma in isolation. 

619
00:56:59,360 --> 00:57:04,000
Some of them I can see look fairly standard 
and resemble something I'm familiar with. 

620
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:06,320
I'm pretty sure there's nothing 
interesting going on there. 

621
00:57:06,320 --> 00:57:12,080
But this other lemma, that's something I haven't 
seen before, and I can see why having this result  

622
00:57:12,080 --> 00:57:19,520
would really help prove the main result.
You can assess whether a step is really key  

623
00:57:21,280 --> 00:57:24,240
to your argument or not, and 
Lean really facilitates that. 

624
00:57:26,240 --> 00:57:28,720
The individual steps are 
identified really precisely. 

625
00:57:29,520 --> 00:57:35,040
I think in the future, there will be entire 
professions of mathematicians who might take  

626
00:57:35,040 --> 00:57:41,120
a giant Lean-generated proof and do some 
ablation on it, trying to remove parts of  

627
00:57:41,120 --> 00:57:46,400
it and find more elegant ways.
They might get other AIs to do  

628
00:57:46,400 --> 00:57:52,160
some reinforcement learning to make the proof 
more elegant, and maybe other AIs will grade  

629
00:57:52,160 --> 00:57:58,000
whether this proof looks better or not.
One thing that will change quite a bit  

630
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:01,920
in the near future is how we write papers.
Until recently, writing papers was the most  

631
00:58:01,920 --> 00:58:07,120
time-consuming and expensive part of the job.
So you did it very rarely. 

632
00:58:07,760 --> 00:58:14,560
You only wrote up your results once all the other 
parts of your argument were checked out, because  

633
00:58:14,560 --> 00:58:19,360
rewriting and refactoring was just a total pain.
That's become a lot easier now  

634
00:58:19,360 --> 00:58:21,600
with modern AI tools.
You don't have to have just  

635
00:58:21,600 --> 00:58:24,960
one version of your paper.
Once you have one,  

636
00:58:24,960 --> 00:58:30,320
people can generate hundreds more.
One giant messy Lean proof may not be very  

637
00:58:31,040 --> 00:58:35,360
meaningful or understandable on 
its own, but other people can  

638
00:58:35,360 --> 00:58:41,680
refactor it and do all kinds of things with it.
We've seen this with the Erdős problem website. 

639
00:58:42,960 --> 00:58:47,840
An AI will generate a proof, and here are 
3,000 lines of code that verify the proof. 

640
00:58:47,840 --> 00:58:52,560
Then people got other AIs to summarize 
the proof, and people write their own  

641
00:58:52,560 --> 00:59:00,480
proofs. There's actually post-processing. 
Once you have one proof, we have a lot of  

642
00:59:00,480 --> 00:59:07,760
tools now to deconstruct and interpret it.
It's a very nascent area of mathematics,  

643
00:59:07,760 --> 00:59:12,000
but I'm not as worried about it.
Some people are concerned about what happens if  

644
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:14,880
the Riemann hypothesis is proven with 
a completely incomprehensible proof. 

645
00:59:14,880 --> 00:59:20,640
I think once you have the artifact of a 
proof, we can do a lot of analysis on it. 

646
00:59:20,640 --> 00:59:24,960
You posted recently that it would be 
helpful to have a formal or semi-formal  

647
00:59:24,960 --> 00:59:28,960
language for mathematical strategies 
as opposed to just mathematical proofs,  

648
00:59:28,960 --> 00:59:32,160
which is what Lean specializes in.
I would love to learn more about  

649
00:59:32,160 --> 00:59:37,840
what that would involve or look like.
We don't really know. We've been very  

650
00:59:37,840 --> 00:59:42,400
lucky in mathematics that we have worked 
out the laws of logic and mathematics,  

651
00:59:42,400 --> 00:59:47,920
but this is a fairly recent accomplishment.
It was started by Euclid two millennia ago,  

652
00:59:47,920 --> 00:59:54,640
but only in the early 20th century did we 
finally list out the axioms of mathematics,  

653
00:59:54,640 --> 00:59:59,600
the standard axioms of what we call ZFC, the 
axioms of first-order logic, and what a proof is. 

654
01:00:00,400 --> 01:00:04,640
This we've managed to automate 
and have a formal language for. 

655
01:00:05,840 --> 01:00:12,960
There could be some way to assess plausibility.
You have a conjecture that something is true,  

656
01:00:14,080 --> 01:00:18,240
you test a few examples, and it works out.
How does this increase your  

657
01:00:18,240 --> 01:00:24,560
confidence that the conjecture is true?
We have a few sort of mathematical ways to model  

658
01:00:24,560 --> 01:00:32,320
this, like Bayesian probability, for example.
But you often have to set certain base  

659
01:00:32,320 --> 01:00:39,440
assumptions, and there's a lot of 
subjectivity still in these tasks. 

660
01:00:44,880 --> 01:00:52,240
This is more of a wish than a plan to develop 
these languages, but just seeing how successful  

661
01:00:52,240 --> 01:00:59,840
having a formal framework in place, like Lean, has 
made deductive proofs so much easier to automate  

662
01:00:59,840 --> 01:01:10,320
and train AI on… The bottleneck for using AI to 
create strategies and make conjectures is we have  

663
01:01:10,320 --> 01:01:16,880
to rely on human experts and the test of time to 
validate whether something is plausible or not. 

664
01:01:16,880 --> 01:01:22,480
If there was some semi-formal framework 
where this could be done semi-automatically  

665
01:01:22,480 --> 01:01:32,240
in a way that isn't easily hackable...
It's really important with these formal  

666
01:01:32,240 --> 01:01:40,720
proof assistants that there are no backdoors 
or exploits you can use to somehow get your  

667
01:01:40,720 --> 01:01:44,960
certified proof without actually proving 
it, because reinforcement learning is  

668
01:01:44,960 --> 01:01:56,160
just so good at finding these backdoors.
If there's some framework that mimics how  

669
01:01:56,160 --> 01:02:01,280
scientists talk to each other in a 
semi-formal way, using data and argument,  

670
01:02:01,280 --> 01:02:08,960
but also constructing narratives...
There's some subjective aspect of  

671
01:02:08,960 --> 01:02:15,680
science that we don't know how to capture in a way 
that we can insert AI into it in any useful way.  

672
01:02:18,160 --> 01:02:25,600
This is a future problem. There are research 
efforts to try to create automated conjectures,  

673
01:02:27,360 --> 01:02:35,440
and maybe there are ways to benchmark these and 
simulate this, but it's all very new science. 

674
01:02:35,440 --> 01:02:45,280
Can you help me get some intuition? I have two 
sub-questions. One, it would be very helpful  

675
01:02:45,280 --> 01:02:56,240
to have a specific example of what something 
like this would look like, the way scientists  

676
01:02:56,240 --> 01:03:02,000
communicate that we can't formalize yet.
Two, it seems almost definitionally paradoxical  

677
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:10,160
to say you're building up some narrative or 
natural language explanation and then also having  

678
01:03:10,160 --> 01:03:16,160
something which you could have formalized.
I'm sure there's some intuition behind  

679
01:03:16,160 --> 01:03:19,680
where that overlap is, and I'd 
love to understand that better. 

680
01:03:20,400 --> 01:03:26,480
An example of a conjecture: Gauss was 
interested in the prime numbers and  

681
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:31,760
created one of the first mathematical datasets.
He just computed the first 100,000 prime numbers  

682
01:03:31,760 --> 01:03:37,120
or so, hoping to find patterns.
He did find a pattern,  

683
01:03:37,120 --> 01:03:41,120
but maybe not the pattern he was expecting.
He found a statistical pattern in the primes  

684
01:03:41,120 --> 01:03:47,520
that if you count how many primes there are 
up to 100, 1,000, one million, and so forth,  

685
01:03:47,520 --> 01:03:54,080
they get sparser and sparser, but the drop-off 
in the density was inversely proportional to  

686
01:03:54,080 --> 01:03:59,360
the natural logarithm of the range of numbers.
So he conjectured what we now call the prime  

687
01:03:59,360 --> 01:04:04,240
number theorem: the number of primes up 
to X is X divided by the natural log of X. 

688
01:04:05,120 --> 01:04:12,080
He had no way to prove this. It was 
data-driven. This was a conjecture.  

689
01:04:12,880 --> 01:04:19,520
It was revolutionary for its time because it 
was maybe the first really important conjecture  

690
01:04:19,520 --> 01:04:23,840
of math that was statistical in nature.
Normally you're talking about a pattern,  

691
01:04:23,840 --> 01:04:26,320
like maybe the spacing between the 
primes has a certain regularity. 

692
01:04:27,600 --> 01:04:32,000
But this didn't tell you exactly how many 
primes there were in any given range. 

693
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:38,880
It just gave you an approximation that got better 
and better as you went further and further out. 

694
01:04:42,640 --> 01:04:45,200
It started the field of what 
we call analytic number theory. 

695
01:04:47,040 --> 01:04:51,040
It was the first in many conjectures 
like this, many of which got proved,  

696
01:04:51,040 --> 01:04:56,880
which started consolidating the idea that the 
prime numbers didn't really have a pattern,  

697
01:04:56,880 --> 01:05:02,720
that they behaved like random sets 
of numbers with a certain density. 

698
01:05:03,360 --> 01:05:05,680
They had some patterns, 
like they're almost all odd. 

699
01:05:07,760 --> 01:05:09,680
They're also not actually random, 
they're what's called pseudo-random. 

700
01:05:10,800 --> 01:05:14,160
There's no random number generation 
involved in creating the prime numbers. 

701
01:05:14,160 --> 01:05:19,600
But over time, it became more and more 
productive to think of the primes as  

702
01:05:19,600 --> 01:05:26,000
if they were just generated by some god rolling 
dice all the time and creating this random set. 

703
01:05:26,000 --> 01:05:27,840
This allowed us to make all 
these other predictions. 

704
01:05:28,480 --> 01:05:32,640
There's a still-open conjecture in number 
theory called the twin prime conjecture, that  

705
01:05:32,640 --> 01:05:37,200
there should be infinitely many pairs of primes 
that are twins just two apart, like 11 and 13. 

706
01:05:37,200 --> 01:05:39,840
We can't prove that, and there are 
good reasons why we can't prove it. 

707
01:05:41,040 --> 01:05:46,240
But because of this statistical random model of 
the primes, we are absolutely convinced it's true. 

708
01:05:46,240 --> 01:05:51,680
We know that if the primes were generated by 
flipping coins, we would just—by random chance  

709
01:05:51,680 --> 01:05:56,240
like infinite monkeys at a typewriter—see 
twin primes appear over and over again. 

710
01:05:57,440 --> 01:06:02,320
We have over time developed this very accurate 
conceptual model of what the primes should behave  

711
01:06:02,320 --> 01:06:07,920
like based on statistics and probability.
It's mostly heuristic and non-rigorous,  

712
01:06:07,920 --> 01:06:12,400
but extremely accurate.
The few times when we actually  

713
01:06:12,400 --> 01:06:16,480
can prove things about the primes, it has 
matched up with the predictions of what we  

714
01:06:16,480 --> 01:06:21,600
call the random model of the primes.
We have this conjectural concept  

715
01:06:21,600 --> 01:06:25,360
framework for understanding the 
primes that everyone believes in. 

716
01:06:25,920 --> 01:06:29,680
It's the same reason why we believe the 
Riemann hypothesis is true, and why we  

717
01:06:29,680 --> 01:06:33,840
believe that cryptography based on 
the primes is mathematically secure. 

718
01:06:35,120 --> 01:06:40,800
It's all part of this belief.
In fact, one reason why we care  

719
01:06:40,800 --> 01:06:44,320
about the Riemann hypothesis is that 
if the Riemann hypothesis failed,  

720
01:06:44,320 --> 01:06:49,200
if we knew it was false, it would 
be a serious blow to this model. 

721
01:06:49,920 --> 01:06:53,360
It would mean there's a secret pattern 
to the primes that we were not aware of. 

722
01:06:54,720 --> 01:06:58,080
I think we would very rapidly abandon 
any cryptography based on the primes,  

723
01:06:58,080 --> 01:07:01,760
because if there was one pattern that we didn't 
know about, there are probably more, and these  

724
01:07:01,760 --> 01:07:07,680
patterns can lead to exploits in crypto.
It would be a big shock. 

725
01:07:07,680 --> 01:07:10,640
So we really want to make 
sure that doesn't happen. 

726
01:07:15,360 --> 01:07:18,960
We've been convinced of things like 
the Riemann hypothesis over time. 

727
01:07:20,320 --> 01:07:24,080
Some of it is experimental evidence, and some 
is that the few times we've been able to make  

728
01:07:24,080 --> 01:07:30,000
theoretical results, they've always aligned.
It is possible that the consensus is wrong and  

729
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:34,720
we've all just missed something very basic.
There have been paradigm shifts in  

730
01:07:34,720 --> 01:07:40,480
the past in scientific history.
But we don't really have a way of  

731
01:07:40,480 --> 01:07:46,800
measuring this, partly because we don't have 
enough data on how math or science develops. 

732
01:07:46,800 --> 01:07:53,600
We have one timeline of history, and we have 
maybe 100 stories of turning points in history. 

733
01:07:53,600 --> 01:07:58,640
If we had access to a million alien 
civilizations, each with a different  

734
01:07:58,640 --> 01:08:04,720
development of history and science in different 
orders, then maybe we'd actually have a decent  

735
01:08:04,720 --> 01:08:12,560
shot at understanding how we measure what 
progress is and what is a good strategy. 

736
01:08:12,560 --> 01:08:16,480
We could maybe start formalizing 
it and actually having a framework. 

737
01:08:18,320 --> 01:08:24,880
Maybe what we need to do is start creating 
lots of mini-universes or simulations of AI  

738
01:08:24,880 --> 01:08:30,240
solving very basic problems in arithmetic 
or whatever, but coming up with their  

739
01:08:30,240 --> 01:08:34,480
own strategies for doing these things and 
having these little laboratories to test. 

740
01:08:34,480 --> 01:08:39,520
There are people who investigate what's 
the smallest neural network that can do  

741
01:08:39,520 --> 01:08:44,800
10-digit multiplication and things like that.
I think we could learn a lot just from evolving  

742
01:08:45,680 --> 01:08:50,880
small AIs on simple problems.
I was super excited when Mercury  

743
01:08:50,880 --> 01:08:54,480
reached out about sponsoring the podcast 
because I've been banking with them for years. 

744
01:08:54,480 --> 01:08:56,720
I think I opened my first 
account with them in 2023. 

745
01:08:56,720 --> 01:08:59,760
Something I've come to appreciate over the 
last few years is that Mercury is constantly  

746
01:08:59,760 --> 01:09:03,440
updating things and adding new features.
Take their newest feature, Insights. 

747
01:09:03,440 --> 01:09:07,360
Insights summarizes your money in and out, 
showing you your biggest transactions and calling  

748
01:09:07,360 --> 01:09:11,680
out anything that deserves extra attention.
Like maybe your revenue from a particular partner  

749
01:09:11,680 --> 01:09:15,440
has gone down, or you've got a big uncategorized 
purchase that needs to be investigated. 

750
01:09:15,440 --> 01:09:19,200
It's a super low-friction way for me to keep 
tabs on my business and make quick decisions. 

751
01:09:19,200 --> 01:09:23,440
For example, I try to invest any cash that I 
don't need on hand to keep running the business. 

752
01:09:23,440 --> 01:09:26,880
With Insights, with just a couple of clicks, 
I was able to see exactly how much money I  

753
01:09:26,880 --> 01:09:31,840
spent in each month of 2025 and that lets 
me know exactly how much cash I'll need for  

754
01:09:31,840 --> 01:09:35,040
the next year or so of operations.
And then I can go invest the rest. 

755
01:09:35,040 --> 01:09:39,760
Mercury just keeps adding new features like this.
Go to mercury.com to check it out. 

756
01:09:39,760 --> 01:09:42,960
Mercury is a fintech company, 
not an FDIC Insured Bank. 

757
01:09:42,960 --> 01:09:48,880
Banking services provided through Choice 
Financial Group and Column NA, members FDIC. 

758
01:09:48,880 --> 01:09:53,440
You have to learn about new fields not 
only very rapidly, but deeply enough  

759
01:09:53,440 --> 01:09:57,200
to contribute to the frontier.
So in some sense, you're also  

760
01:09:57,200 --> 01:10:04,800
one of the world's greatest autodidacts.
What is your process of learning about a new  

761
01:10:04,800 --> 01:10:12,480
subfield in math? What does that look like?
We talked about depth and breadth before. 

762
01:10:12,480 --> 01:10:19,360
It's not a purely human-AI distinction.
Humans also, I think it was Berlin who  

763
01:10:19,360 --> 01:10:23,280
split them into hedgehogs and foxes.
The hedgehog knows one thing very well,  

764
01:10:23,280 --> 01:10:30,080
and a fox knows a little bit about everything.
I definitely think of myself as a fox. 

765
01:10:32,240 --> 01:10:35,360
I work with hedgehogs a lot, and 
sometimes I can be a hedgehog if need be. 

766
01:10:40,240 --> 01:10:43,280
I've always had a little 
bit of an obsessive streak. 

767
01:10:43,280 --> 01:10:48,480
If there's something I read about which I 
feel like I have the capability to understand,  

768
01:10:48,480 --> 01:10:53,680
but I don't understand why it works and 
there's some magic in it… Someone was able  

769
01:10:53,680 --> 01:10:58,320
to use a type of mathematics I'm not familiar 
with and get a result I would like to prove. 

770
01:10:58,320 --> 01:11:01,440
I can't do it myself, but they 
could do it by their method,  

771
01:11:01,440 --> 01:11:06,800
and I want to find out what their trick was.
It bugs me that someone else can do something  

772
01:11:06,800 --> 01:11:10,960
I think I can do, but I can't.
I've always had that obsessive,  

773
01:11:10,960 --> 01:11:14,160
completionist streak.
I've had to wean myself off  

774
01:11:14,160 --> 01:11:20,160
computer games because if I start a game, I want 
to play it to completion, through all the levels. 

775
01:11:23,840 --> 01:11:29,840
That's one way I learn new fields.
I collaborate with a lot of people  

776
01:11:29,840 --> 01:11:35,520
who have taught me other types of mathematics.
I just make friends with another mathematician  

777
01:11:35,520 --> 01:11:38,880
working on another area of mathematics.
I find their problems interesting,  

778
01:11:38,880 --> 01:11:44,480
but they have to teach me some of the basic 
tricks, what's known, and what's not known. 

779
01:11:44,480 --> 01:11:48,960
I learn a lot from that.
I found that writing about  

780
01:11:49,840 --> 01:11:52,400
what I've learned helps.
I have a blog where I sometimes  

781
01:11:54,800 --> 01:11:58,320
record things I've learned.
In the past when I was younger,  

782
01:11:58,320 --> 01:12:02,240
I would learn something, do this cool trick, 
and say, "Okay, I'm going to remember this." 

783
01:12:02,240 --> 01:12:06,160
Then six months later, I'd forgotten it.
I remember remembering it,  

784
01:12:07,440 --> 01:12:11,040
but I can't reconstruct my arguments.
The first few times, it was so frustrating  

785
01:12:11,040 --> 01:12:16,960
to have understood something and then lost it.
I resolved I should always write down  

786
01:12:16,960 --> 01:12:22,160
anything cool that I've learned.
That's part of how this blog came about. 

787
01:12:22,720 --> 01:12:27,840
How long does it take you to write a blog post?
It's something I often do when I don't want  

788
01:12:27,840 --> 01:12:30,160
to do other work.
There's some referee  

789
01:12:30,160 --> 01:12:34,560
report or something that feels slightly 
unpleasant for me to do at the time. 

790
01:12:35,760 --> 01:12:39,840
Writing a blog feels creative and fun.
It's something I do for myself. 

791
01:12:42,400 --> 01:12:46,720
Depending on the topic, it could be a 
quick half an hour or several hours. 

792
01:12:49,360 --> 01:12:58,000
Because it's something I do voluntarily, 
time flies when I write these things down, as  

793
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:03,680
opposed to doing something I have to do for 
administrative reasons that is just drudgery. 

794
01:13:03,680 --> 01:13:06,080
Those are tasks, by the way, that 
AI is really helping with nowadays. 

795
01:13:07,760 --> 01:13:14,560
If civilization could from first principles 
decide how to use Terry Tao's time, as a  

796
01:13:14,560 --> 01:13:22,480
limited resource, what is the biggest difference?
What if the veil of ignorance got to decide how to  

797
01:13:22,480 --> 01:13:28,320
use Terry Tao's time versus what it does 
now? This podcast wouldn't be happening. 

798
01:13:29,760 --> 01:13:34,720
As much as I complain about certain tasks that 
I don't want to do, but have to do… As you get  

799
01:13:34,720 --> 01:13:39,920
more senior in academia, you get more and more 
responsibilities, more committees, and whatever. 

800
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:47,680
I have also found that a lot of events 
I reluctantly went to because I was  

801
01:13:47,680 --> 01:13:51,600
obliged to for one reason or another… 
Because it's outside my comfort zone,  

802
01:13:51,600 --> 01:13:56,480
it often results in interactions with people I 
wouldn't normally talk to, like you for instance. 

803
01:13:57,520 --> 01:14:00,000
I would learn interesting things 
and have interesting experiences. 

804
01:14:01,760 --> 01:14:07,440
I would have opportunities to then network with 
other people that I never would have before. 

805
01:14:08,160 --> 01:14:18,000
So I do believe a lot in serendipity.
I do optimize portions of my day  

806
01:14:18,000 --> 01:14:24,720
where I schedule very carefully.
But I am willing to leave some portions just  

807
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:29,600
to do something that is not my usual thing.
Maybe it'll be a waste of my time,  

808
01:14:29,600 --> 01:14:38,160
but maybe I will learn something.
More often than not, I get a positive  

809
01:14:38,160 --> 01:14:44,000
experience that I wouldn't have planned for.
So I believe a lot in serendipity. 

810
01:14:45,360 --> 01:14:50,080
Maybe there's a danger in modern 
societies, not just with AI, that we've  

811
01:14:50,080 --> 01:14:57,440
become really good at optimizing everything.
We’re not optimizing our own optimization. 

812
01:14:59,440 --> 01:15:06,640
With COVID, for example, we switched a lot to 
remote meetings, so everything was scheduled.  

813
01:15:07,920 --> 01:15:14,480
We kept busy in academia. We met almost 
the same number of people we met in person,  

814
01:15:14,480 --> 01:15:22,640
but everything had to be planned in advance.
What we lost out on was the casual knocking  

815
01:15:22,640 --> 01:15:26,240
on a hallway door, just meeting 
someone while getting a coffee. 

816
01:15:28,000 --> 01:15:37,200
Those serendipitous interactions may not seem 
optimal, but they are actually really important. 

817
01:15:37,200 --> 01:15:42,640
When I was a grad student, I would go to 
the library to look for a journal article. 

818
01:15:42,640 --> 01:15:46,960
You had to physically check out 
the journal and read the article. 

819
01:15:46,960 --> 01:15:51,440
You could browse through and sometimes 
the next article was also interesting. 

820
01:15:52,160 --> 01:15:56,240
Sometimes it wasn’t, but you could 
accidentally find interesting things. 

821
01:15:56,960 --> 01:16:02,080
That has basically been lost now.
If you want to access an article,  

822
01:16:02,080 --> 01:16:06,480
you just type it into a search engine or an AI, 
and you get exactly what you want instantly. 

823
01:16:06,480 --> 01:16:13,840
But you don't get the accidental things you might 
have found if you'd done it more inefficiently. 

824
01:16:20,320 --> 01:16:23,920
I spent a year once at the Institute 
for Advanced Study, which is  

825
01:16:23,920 --> 01:16:28,880
a great place with no distractions.
You're there just to do research. 

826
01:16:29,440 --> 01:16:33,120
The first few weeks you're there, it's great.
You're getting all these papers written up that  

827
01:16:33,120 --> 01:16:35,440
you've been wanting to do for a long time.
You think about problems for  

828
01:16:35,440 --> 01:16:39,040
blocks of hours at a time.
But I find if I stay there for more  

829
01:16:39,040 --> 01:16:46,880
than several months, I run out of inspiration. 
I get bored. I surf the internet a lot more. 

830
01:16:46,880 --> 01:16:50,080
You actually do need a certain 
level of distraction in your life. 

831
01:16:50,080 --> 01:17:02,560
It adds enough randomness and high temperature.
I don't know the optimal way to schedule  

832
01:17:02,560 --> 01:17:08,000
my life. It just seems to work.
I'm very curious when you expect AIs  

833
01:17:08,000 --> 01:17:15,360
that can actually do frontier math at least 
as well as the best human mathematicians. 

834
01:17:15,920 --> 01:17:21,360
In some ways, they're already doing frontier math 
that is super intelligent that humans can't do,  

835
01:17:21,360 --> 01:17:23,600
but it's a different frontier 
from what we're used to. 

836
01:17:24,320 --> 01:17:29,440
You could argue that calculators were doing 
frontier math that humans could not accomplish,  

837
01:17:29,440 --> 01:17:38,800
but it was number crunching.
But replacing Terry Tao completely. 

838
01:17:38,800 --> 01:17:48,000
I mean, what do you want me for?
You'll just go on all the podcasts after. 

839
01:17:50,800 --> 01:18:01,040
It might not be the right question to ask.
I think within a decade, a lot of things that  

840
01:18:01,040 --> 01:18:06,320
math students currently do—what we spend the 
bulk of our time doing and a lot of stuff we  

841
01:18:06,320 --> 01:18:12,720
put in our papers today—can be done by AI.
But we will find that that actually wasn't  

842
01:18:12,720 --> 01:18:20,400
the most important part of what we do.
A hundred years ago, a lot of mathematicians  

843
01:18:20,400 --> 01:18:26,080
were just solving differential equations.
Physicists needed some exact solution to  

844
01:18:27,440 --> 01:18:33,200
some system, and they hired a mathematician to 
laboriously go through the calculus and work out  

845
01:18:33,200 --> 01:18:40,000
the solution to this fluid equation, whatever.
A lot of what a 19th-century mathematician would  

846
01:18:40,000 --> 01:18:46,320
do, you could make a call to Mathematica, Wolfram 
Alpha, a computer algebra package, or now more  

847
01:18:46,320 --> 01:18:53,120
recently to an AI, and it would just solve the 
problem in a few minutes. But we moved on. We  

848
01:18:53,120 --> 01:18:57,840
worked on different types of problems after that.
Once computers came along—computers  

849
01:18:59,120 --> 01:19:01,040
used to be human.
People used to laboriously  

850
01:19:01,040 --> 01:19:05,920
create log tables and work out primes as 
Gauss did, and that has all been outsourced  

851
01:19:05,920 --> 01:19:16,080
to computers. But we moved on. In genetics, 
to sequence the genome of a single organism,  

852
01:19:16,080 --> 01:19:23,440
that was an entire PhD of a geneticist, carefully 
separating all the chromosomes and whatever. 

853
01:19:23,440 --> 01:19:26,800
Now you can just spend $1,000 and send 
it to a sequencer and get it done. 

854
01:19:26,800 --> 01:19:31,040
But genetics is not dead as a subject.
You move to a different scale. 

855
01:19:31,040 --> 01:19:34,160
Maybe you study whole ecosystems 
rather than individuals. 

856
01:19:34,160 --> 01:19:38,320
I take your point but when is most 
mathematical progress, or almost  

857
01:19:38,320 --> 01:19:43,200
all mathematical progress, happening by AI?
If you find out this year a Millennium Prize  

858
01:19:43,200 --> 01:19:49,840
Problem has been solved, you would put 
95% odds that an AI did it autonomously. 

859
01:19:49,840 --> 01:19:56,720
Surely there will be such a year.
I guess I do believe that hybrid  

860
01:19:57,600 --> 01:20:04,720
human plus AIs will dominate mathematics for 
a lot longer. It will depend. It will require  

861
01:20:04,720 --> 01:20:09,840
some additional breakthroughs beyond what we 
already have, so it's going to be stochastic. 

862
01:20:11,120 --> 01:20:15,200
I think AIs currently are very good at 
certain things, but really terrible at others. 

863
01:20:16,560 --> 01:20:23,360
While you can add more and more frameworks on top 
to reduce the error rates and make them work with  

864
01:20:23,360 --> 01:20:33,360
each other a bit more, it feels like we don't 
have all the ingredients to really have a truly  

865
01:20:33,360 --> 01:20:40,320
satisfactory replacement for all intellectual 
tasks. It is complementary currently. It's not  

866
01:20:42,720 --> 01:20:54,320
a replacement. Because current level AIs 
will accelerate science in so many ways,  

867
01:20:54,320 --> 01:21:00,000
hopefully new discoveries and new 
breakthroughs will happen more quickly. 

868
01:21:01,200 --> 01:21:06,400
It's also possible that by destroying serendipity 
we actually inhibit certain types of progress. 

869
01:21:07,200 --> 01:21:11,040
Anything is possible at this point.
I think the world is very,  

870
01:21:11,040 --> 01:21:16,400
very unpredictable at this point in time.
What is your advice to somebody who would  

871
01:21:16,400 --> 01:21:25,680
consider a career in math or is early in a career 
in math, especially in light of AI progress? 

872
01:21:25,680 --> 01:21:27,680
How should they be thinking about 
their career differently, if at all,  

873
01:21:27,680 --> 01:21:31,280
as a result of AI progress?
We live in a time of change. 

874
01:21:32,480 --> 01:21:36,080
As I said, we live in a 
particularly unpredictable era. 

875
01:21:41,280 --> 01:21:45,680
Things that we've taken for granted 
for centuries may not hold anymore. 

876
01:21:48,240 --> 01:21:54,080
The way we do everything, and not 
just mathematics, will change. 

877
01:21:59,600 --> 01:22:03,280
In many ways, I would prefer the much more 
boring, quiet era where things are much the  

878
01:22:03,280 --> 01:22:11,280
same as they were 10 years ago, 20 years ago.
But I think one just has to embrace that  

879
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:18,560
there's going to be a lot of change.
The things that you study, some of them  

880
01:22:18,560 --> 01:22:23,120
may become obsolete or revolutionized, 
but some things will be retained. 

881
01:22:26,720 --> 01:22:35,200
You always have to keep an eye on opportunities 
for things that you wouldn't be able to do before. 

882
01:22:37,680 --> 01:22:42,240
In math, you previously had to go through 
years and years of education and be a math  

883
01:22:42,240 --> 01:22:45,040
PhD before you could contribute 
to the frontier of math research. 

884
01:22:46,160 --> 01:22:49,040
But now it's quite possible at the 
high school level, or whatever,  

885
01:22:49,040 --> 01:22:52,320
that you could get involved in a math project and 
actually make a real contribution because of all  

886
01:22:52,320 --> 01:22:58,160
these AI tools, Lean, and everything else.
There will be a lot of non-traditional  

887
01:22:58,160 --> 01:23:04,080
opportunities to learn, so you 
need a very adaptable mindset. 

888
01:23:06,640 --> 01:23:10,560
There will be room for pursuing things 
just for curiosity and for playing around. 

889
01:23:11,840 --> 01:23:16,160
You still need to get your credentials.
For a while it will still be important to  

890
01:23:17,440 --> 01:23:23,920
go through traditional education and learn 
math and science the old-fashioned way. 

891
01:23:28,080 --> 01:23:35,680
But you should also be open to very different ways 
of doing science, some of which don't exist yet. 

892
01:23:37,360 --> 01:23:42,320
It's a scary time, but also very exciting.
That's a great note to close on. Terence,  

893
01:23:42,320 --> 01:23:43,280
thanks so much.
Pleasure.

